{"id":479,"date":"2021-10-26T21:59:48","date_gmt":"2021-10-26T21:59:48","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/?page_id=479"},"modified":"2021-10-28T01:05:00","modified_gmt":"2021-10-28T01:05:00","slug":"ac-love","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/ac-love\/","title":{"rendered":"Algorithmic Composition- Love(2021)"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p> <strong><em>Keywords: Midi Art, Monte Carlo Method, (x\u00b2+y\u00b2-1)\u00b3 =x\u00b2y\u00b3<\/em> <\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\"><strong>Abstract:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>&#8220;Love&#8221; is an algorithmic composition that uses a variant of the Monto Carlo Method to approximate a heart shape on a Midi piano roll.  In this composition, I map a mathematical equation,  (x\u00b2+y\u00b2-1)\u00b3 =x\u00b2y\u00b3, to a midi piano roll, where x represents midi event onset time and y represents the Midi key number. After spawning multiple midi events, I put it into a General Midi sample bank, GM_No_31_Electric_Guitar, to create an effect of language speaking from a semi-Sapien creature. Yes, what I want to reveal here is when a man falls in love, his logos will loom away and leave a place for his tempestuous sentiment.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\"><strong>Music:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/love.mp3\"><\/audio><figcaption>Love.mp3<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\"><strong>MIDI Download:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-file\"><a href=\"https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/love_midi_download.mid\">love_midi_download<\/a><a href=\"https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/love_midi_download.mid\" class=\"wp-block-file__button\" download>Download<\/a><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\"><strong>Screenshots of the project:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code># Musx is an algorithmic compostion framework created by Professor Heinrick Taube at UIUC \n# Install musx package through pip install musx \n\n# Import info and some functions are omitted, if you need source code, please contact: sz18@illinois.edu, Benny Zhang\n\n\ndef get_single_love(time_scale, pitch_scale):\n    '''\n    return two lists x, y including the relative coordinate of the heart shapae\n    '''\n    x_lower_bound = -1.25\n    x_upper_bound = 1.25\n    y_lower_bound = -1\n    y_upper_bound = 1.25\n    x_ord =&#91;item for item in musx.frange(x_lower_bound,x_upper_bound,0.001)]\n    y_ord =&#91;item for item in musx.frange(y_lower_bound,y_upper_bound,0.001)]\n    ord_set = &#91;]\n    gran = 0.00000000001\n    for i in range(len(x_ord)):\n        for j in range(len(y_ord)):\n            if math.pow(math.pow(x_ord&#91;i], 2) + math.pow(y_ord&#91;j], 2) - 1, 3) - (math.pow(x_ord&#91;i],2) * math.pow(y_ord&#91;j],3)) &lt;= gran:\n                ord_set.append((x_ord&#91;i],y_ord&#91;j]))\n    sample_num = 1147\n    sampled_ord = &#91;]\n    for i in range(sample_num):\n        sampled_ord.append(ord_set&#91;i*int((len(ord_set)\/sample_num))])\n    #plot(sampled_ord)\n\n    sampled_x = &#91;item&#91;0] for item in sampled_ord]; \n    sampled_y = &#91;item&#91;1] for item in sampled_ord]\n\n    xmin=min(sampled_x); xmax= max(sampled_x)\n    ymin=min(sampled_y); ymax= max(sampled_y)\n    rescaled_x = &#91;]\n    rescaled_y = &#91;]\n    for i in range(len(sampled_x)):\n        rescaled_x.append(musx.rescale(sampled_x&#91;i],xmin,xmax,0, time_scale))\n        rescaled_y.append(musx.rescale(sampled_y&#91;i],ymin,ymax,pitch_scale&#91;0], pitch_scale&#91;1]))\n\n    return &#91;rescaled_x, rescaled_y]\n\n\ndef mutate_pheno_1(q,coord):\n    #print(coord&#91;0])\n    for i in range(len(coord&#91;0])-1):\n        now = coord&#91;0]&#91;i]; nex  = coord&#91;0]&#91;i+1]\n        print(now)\n        note = MidiNote(time=q.now, dur=choice(&#91;0.1,0.15]), amp=choice(&#91;0.2,0.3,0.6]), key=int(coord&#91;1]&#91;i]), chan=choice(&#91;0,1,2,3,9]))\n        q.out.addevent(note)\n        yield nex-now\n\n\ndef love():\n    t0 = MidiSeq.metaseq(ins={0: DistortionGuitar})\n    seq = MidiSeq()\n    queue = Scheduler(out=seq)\n    time_scale = 20\n    pitch_scale = &#91;30, 90]\n    coord = get_single_love(time_scale, pitch_scale)\n\n    A = mutate_pheno_1(queue, coord)\n    queue.compose(&#91;0, A])\n    MidiFile(\"love.mid\", &#91;t0]).write()  \n\n# Start\nlove()<\/code><\/pre>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"757\" height=\"751\" src=\"https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/midi_love-1-3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-546\" srcset=\"https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/midi_love-1-3.png 757w, https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/midi_love-1-3-300x298.png 300w, https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/midi_love-1-3-150x150.png 150w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 757px) 100vw, 757px\" \/><figcaption>Fig.1 A collage of love.mid<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/love.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-555\" width=\"832\" height=\"624\" srcset=\"https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/love.png 640w, https:\/\/shichengzhang.web.illinois.edu\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/10\/love-300x225.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 832px) 100vw, 832px\" \/><figcaption>Fig.2 A Matplotlib plotting for the Monte Carlo Method for love.mid<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Keywords: Midi Art, Monte Carlo Method, (x\u00b2+y\u00b2